commentBody:
@Sam Lyons 

You got me wondering whether crossing NIHILO with NILS violates some crossword rule, being that they are basically the same word.




Inquiring emus want to know....

@Darian 
A NIT is a louse egg. (Don't ask me how I know that.)



🐜🐜🐜

@Jon G. 

I don't think so.  I solved on a desktop, but then looked at my iPhone to see what the deal was.  I didn't have the option to update the app, so I already had the latest version.

Sometime overnight, someone on the tech crew fixed the problem, which was apparently in the coding for this specific puzzle, and specific to iOs (it worked fine for Android).

@Andrzej 

TCBY = The Country's Best Yogurt (frozen yogurt franchise).

PEE is the spelling of the letter "P"; CUE is the spelling of the letter "Q". LMNOP then Q.

@Kerri 

Its referencing the saying “Mind your P’s and Q’s”.


I think it means “behave yourself” (but could be wrong on that!)

@Anne 
😂 Oh yeah. Forgot about the alphabet. (Thought I was clever)

In fairness, I *could* be right. We don’t actually *know* if the constructor was thinking about the alphabet or the rather obscure saying.

@Patrick J. 

How long ago did you solve?  Apparently, some changes were made overnight (NY time) that solved the problem that people were having when the puzzle first came out.

(The circles that now appear are still pretty faint.)

@GFE 

The answer is WHEN THE TIME COMES, but you have to go around the loops (circles) to get it.

...................................................

@Deb Amlen -- Nor did I find the comment remotely objectionable.  The puzzle was "just not for her".  Considering the vertiginous and confusing  quality of the puzzle, that's more than enough "rationale" for me. 
Does Julia really need to specify each and every LOOP she "hate-solved"?

Bottom line for me: As long as you make sure to hate the puzzle and not the puzzlemaker, you are not being especially unkind, and you are CERTAINLY not being uncivil.  I speak as a constructor who has had plenty of my rebuses hated by the rebus-haters and even had some of what I like to think of as my most sparkling wordplay hated by the anti-punners.   Unless they say something mean about me, it rolls right off my back. I know that no puzzle can be everything to everyone.  Take today, for instance.  There seems to be no end of people who simply love going in circles, even though I'm hard-pressed to say why:)

@Mean Old Lady 
Eric, I meant to protest your dismissive treatment of the 1957 hit.  I had no idea from the clue, (wasn't it too soon to name a band after that dreadful Ford model?) but RAM gave me the rest of the phrase and the trick to the puzzle.  
Next you'll say something mean about OO-ee-oo-ah-ah, ting-tang, walla-walla bing-bang!

@Mean Old Lady 

Thanks, but I’d rather not have to fire up the iMac and the printer, and find something to write with and on, when it’s so much easier to just grab my iPad. 

Plus, I don’t want to miss the occasional animations on completion of the puzzle. The little motorcycle rider in the Evel Knievel puzzle a few months ago was better than anything else in that puzzle.

@Mean Old Lady 

Sounds like you are on the road to recovery, back to your Mean Old Self and I'm glad to hear it.  The circles were quite faint on my copy too and had to have the toner on full blast.  

I was very satisfied with sETTLE for "Resolve" which really held things up in that crossing.

@Xword Junkie 
My criticism of the puzzle is the same as yours: clever theme, but resorting to a 1950's song title as a theme answer which is both nonsensical (i.e. not readily inferred) and, in my mind, not a common cultural reference, turns what should be a fun "aha" into a not-so-fun "uh, maybe?" 

Then, cross that answer with another (BAL) that is likely only regionally known and also can't be inferred, and I think that's should have been flagged as a construction flaw that needed to be fixed.

@David Connell 
I'd say you're in fine fettle today.

I did not know the meaning of ASANA, so thanks for that. Sanskrit was not offered at my school...but JAMON was a gimme.

@sunny617 

Easy on the rebus-hating.  
You're really serious about being a puzzle ace, you'll learn to love'em.

@Kiki Rijkstra 

Sorry you are having this trouble.  I went back and checked my settings (Win10/Chrome) and the actual setting is "Fit to printable area".   The other option offered is "Print to paper" which works ok too on an HP Laser P1006. 

A possible workaround is to download the file instead of printing it from the browser then opening it in Adobe Reader which may give you more options.

@Bemused, badgered, and beleaguered 


...but look at how long some of the Revealer clues are!  
We wuz robbed!

@Eva H. 

You left the -r off the last word in your post!



Emu food

@LBG 
It's " than I"-- but you knew that.

You are a contributor, too!

@Gig 

On another comment, I just said "as a Gen-X girl, THREEPIO was a gimme". What I didn't add but thought about is that I was 10 when I got to see Star Wars in a theater when it launched. How about that??

I never did become particularly engaged with the franchise. But every time I would catch that first movie on cable, I'd watch it all the way through. Still love it!

@G 

I seriously love every single thing about your comment here... And could not agree more!!

By the way, for my 40th birthday, which was some undisclosed number of Gen X years ago, I made my closest loved ones come to a local county fair and ride the Tilt-a-Whirl with me! Hahaha! Well I didn't actually *make* them but I did request it and most of them complied!  😆

@JP 

I found it very fun and satisfying!

I'm glad that the NY Times provides a variety of puzzles for the wonderful variety of solvers there are!!

@Happy 
I am just amazed that you could solve this without the circles.  I never could have…

Don’t think the emus will let this through, but I just don’t care.

@UCCF 
I did the exact same thing! Both answers are correct even though they mean different things. It was only when I got to 25D that I realized it was not "sETTLE".

.............................................

@BrianQ 

Wouldn't ACT AS ONE mean just the opposite of "Have no co-conspirators"?

(Only more than one person can ACT AS ONE; one person simply IS one.)

@Robert Nailling 
....and are not happy.  

Poor things.

@Darian
Nits are head lice.  A madrasa is an Islamic school.  A nob is an old-fashioned word for a head.  An asana is any kind of yoga pose.

I might have got those, but I'm still trying to understand "sadd", so if you can explain that to me, I'll be grateful!

@Warren 

Did you ever want to pull a letter back after dropping it in a mailbox?

I suppose multiple sects share the single symbol.

@Jon Mark 

Both  meanings work.

Emus are less flexible, perhaps.

@Wayne Johnson -- So man / Settle vs My man / Mettle - great way to trick us with resolve (verb) = settle vs resolve (noun) = mettle :D 

Also btw the puzzle hint is correct that Sadat was the first Muslim Nobel Laureate (1978) -- Abdus Salam was the first in Physics (1979), not overall. Didn't mean to suggest it wasn't correct. I took a while trying to rebus the 12 letters into 6 spaces ! or first name vs last name

I really liked the loop de loop thing :)

@Roberto

The crosses were not hard for me to get ... except for the one I didn't.

Bal Harbour is Natick to me.

@Hardroch 

The emus are sleeping with their headstucked under their wings....
Good to see you.

@Kiki Rijkstra 

Today's PDF's were limited to the Newspaper version because the staff either can't or won't render "special characters" such as the circles in today's grid.  

If you fiddle with the printer settings, usually selecting "Fit to Page",  you can get everything to print properly.  The exact settings would depend on your computer and printer set up (I'm assuming you are using a PC or MAC).

@calhouri 
That is truly admirable persistence.
You are a steely-eyed rocket....er, puzzle-solver!
